Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament has today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the exclusion of the minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes at second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison by the alleged signature of an agreement with Russia disadvantaged to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is still not final, the Court of Appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there had been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal for the withdrawal of paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code against the former Prime Minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
For approval, 226 votes were required.
