How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold travel only to the socialist bloc in most cases, as travels to the West were very restricted.
The Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime bowed to the west and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Yet not all was won.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable person", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way in which the Czechs travel has suffered since 1989 has been a genuine revolution.
While until 1989 it was not for us to spend vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989, could not be travelled freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to the neighbouring States of Western Europe, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see any tarts from the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czech groups in the parks were sleeping in tents, as our income back then did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take the food with it (conservatives, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased, and with it also average wages, which led to an increase in travel demand around 1997.
With the increased demand for travel the agencies began, starting in 1997 regularly, to prepare the trips using charter flights connections, which led to an incredible decrease in travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs were travelling visaless to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been leaving each year, making distant and hot countries. This winter will now fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit them about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses on the accommodation site.
