Legends about traps in school and university exams are very extensive.
There have been cases in which teachers have given students the responses to the exams in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out deep research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been overturned.
The liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, bluff, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the declaration, microfacet expressions, question formation and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or negotiation management.
The good liars have the ability to read well for others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies", while women say more "orientated lies to others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their couples than those who are not married (but the lies they often say tend to be "enorms").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a base line."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Notice the posture of the subject, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better to know if someone usually hits with his foot all the time not to make unfair accusations when he sees his feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavioural groups.
Consider these behavioural groups as warning signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their history, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change their posture significantly, or expose a "post-interview sketch" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions have ended.
Interviewers often falsely point out that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his leg to the bottom and used the past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I haven't had sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... until I understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
