"Lady Marmalade"'s 18-month-old singer, who suffered " personality changes, sleep disorders" and "increased her fear of strangers," says her family in the Manhattan Supreme Court.
It was November 10 last year when Tramoist Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were getting ready to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk took the car, Roseanna Monk went down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with his luggage, taking Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stopped by the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
"Someone came up behind me and said, "Do you know what your daughter is doing?" I said, "Yes, and I went to get her," he said.
LaBelle warned the pregnant woman that she was angry.
"He said in an aggressive tone, "I shouldn't have left your daughter near the door," said Roseanna Monk.
"I said, "I have no interest in what you say or think."
He became angry and began to use bad words - word C and word J aloud...
He had a bottle of water and he started throwing the water out of the bottle on me."
He said Genevieve went hysterical.
"I told this woman, "Look what you did to my daughter," the girl's mother said.
LaBelle leaned over the mother -- who was still holding Genevieve -- and had to be contained by her environment and retreated to a car waiting for her, Roseanna Monk said.
The little girl was crying so loud she threw up, she added.
Later, the family sent a note asking for an apology from LaBelle, but there was no reply.
The lawyer and the representatives of LaBelle did not return the calls to comment on what happened.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but family attorney Sam Davis said he took the case free of charge and that the family plans to donate all the money it gets to a support association for children with cancer.
"The purpose is to make Patti LaBelle responsible for his behavior," Davis said.
"That kind of behavior is completely unacceptable, especially when it comes to a kindergarten teacher who takes an 18-month-old child in her arms."
Climate Adversity Slowed the Economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-named of change, which generated great expectations about the economic progress, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses to the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of damage to the ice creams, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was caused in 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the main sinister crops were vegetables, corn and garb.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed accelerated growth, as, from January to March 55,053 signalers were unemployed, with a 4.53 per cent rate of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate increased to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in number of people dropped to more than 74,000 unemployed signalers, an increase in the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have taken since public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market for the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation passed at the congress to combat money laundering, already for people who seize dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Organisation
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already have many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the signal labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in the state is not working as a worker in any social security institution.
Added to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labour revenues is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Insurance Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, far below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decrease in Direct Foreign Investment over the last 10 years has been recorded, according to the Ministry of Economic Affairs from January to June of State FDI amounted to $630,697, representing a decrease of 87,74 per cent compared to the $5 million,143,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos per year, mainly from tertiary sector enterprises.
Debt
In light of the economic contraction scenario, the State Government requested in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, the same as investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of revitalizing the economy, the approval of the local congress was for a sum of 2 billion pesos, and until November they had not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was no harmonisation of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we failed to align the effort of everyone and above all the good already synchronized march of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as early-year ice-cream stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including ices, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that has not returned fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year, we are closing far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he said that it is necessary to refer the state to productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefine, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to be done
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better shape the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been working to achieve good results in different areas of economic development, there is some progress but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has made progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
