Valid "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog digital signals is one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that precedes the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, by not gathering the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and the decree remains in force.
The draft judgment, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favour of the project they voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and in admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the implementation of the decree and all the actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The full of ministers also decided to dismiss the demand brought by the House of Deputies, without entering the project discussion, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the President-in-Office said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the preparation of the public administration.
"I also do not think that if it were to be done, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector would be the federal executive, who has constitutional mandate, the state rectory.
Replacement of analog digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and it translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would be to delay the benefits of digitization, which involves a decision of public interest, which does not only have a technical dimension, "for covering economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire system established, according to the principle of economic rectory of the State, to include a group of powers which the Constitution leads to the power of the state executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition, and had done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in some way violates the area of competence of Congress, since compliance with the laws issued by the legislature is being provided in the administrative field, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a vote-by-vote count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PPR, the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of the count "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process of this year in Michoacán, where according to the data presented by the Pre-Trial Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (EMI), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacan did not approve its Political Constitution or the Electoral Code of the State or the Electoral Justice Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the completion of the legal period so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for in the State's Official Journal Act, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the vote of the State's representative to constitutional reforms as invalid and illegal, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal stated that through the approval of the relevant guidelines by the General Council of the EMI it will be possible to make partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be assumed that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and calculation in the case file or does not work with the President of the Chamber; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the boxes of the election may be made when there is evidence that the difference between the alleged candidate who wins the election concerned and the one who has obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition who applied to the second of the candidates indicated.
The total counting of the vote may also be made if, at the end of the ordinary calculation, the difference between the alleged winner and the second successful candidate is equal or lower to a percentage point, provided that the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate remained second, in which case the electoral packages which have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation the choice of Morelia is found, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although not counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
