The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster
The Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of the economic disaster and has put the whole eurozone at risk.
A presidential communiqué announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will assume office.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "frame is now well outlined," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain the beaten trust in Italy.
Stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the performance of the Italian BTP bonds 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
The possibilities for Monti's success were considerably driven by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced the resignation on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the government of the most technocratic majority that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti Government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what would likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks came under pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti started on Monday his consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
Monti has said that his government should last until the forthcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections go ahead.
Monti has said that he would like to include politicians in his office, but the big parties insist that he should be formed only by technicians, an indication of his repairs to a process that is forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
