The grouping is located in the South American wing of its two-decade work tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only scale in Central America.
That day will be presented at the National Stadium, beginning at 7:30 p.m., next to the angelic band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose complete transcription is in The Nation on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, is it a dream realized that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are you aware of what their fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I've been in Costa Rica just once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we'll be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to take our music there.
I wonder because there is a kind of devotion to the band, fans live in intensity the previous days.
What do they say to their most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for having waited so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add some pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've had during the last 21 years have occurred during the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo, and we hope that this set us up for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they've been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we've never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this for?
I think it's partially because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and each one likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we've been keeping from touching, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years' journey.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they've accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined that we would be in a big rock band and have done it for over 20 years now that it looks like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are thrilled that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world where we always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the grunt's rise?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of big bands.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement arises from a group of friends and it's a little unusual.
From time to time, a band of a city emerges, but it is much more strange when five or ten bands go out at the same time in a city.
We are proud and honoured to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be friends of all of them still and honor us to be part of that sound of Seattle that came up.
It is also very odd that a band like yours will remain united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Camron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we are all lucky to be alive and secondly, we all worry about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we've grown, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure that you don't stay on tour because it's easy to fall into that game of the great crowds and the people who love your music.
While you remember that people are there for music, that reminds you that you must respect music and what brought it, without being encapsulated for being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never published a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were many frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think of the incredible person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, to laugh, to talk about music and soccer and much more.
He was a surprising human being and we missed him.
The Las Robertas national band will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose it for opening?
Yes, production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked most, so we look forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and have to be very entertaining.
Why do Yellow Ledbetter's lyrics always change live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that happens to him.
As a bassist, what are their influences?
They're so many.
Among the first things that happen to me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunt relevant even though it is no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's a wonderful thing because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and has now become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might look more light, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs though they may sound a little bit positive.
With both, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they were deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a relative or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt they represent that for me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
