Fujimori is hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday in a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his head doctor reported.
Fujimori, 72, who has served a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including cancer in the language for which he has been operated four times and is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV Channel N that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of force of its lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate for the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he is known to be innocent.
It has been operated four times from cancer to the tongue, it has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added, such as severe erosion, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, hypertension, and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in detention since September 2007 at the National Directorate for Special Operations of the Police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilater who operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official committee, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican pair, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "proper for the exchange of information in all the political affairs between the two nations", according to the South American Presidency published on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France arising when French agent Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's rejection and the call to consult its Ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20, a group of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world since November, and has been in force with the South American country, since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the establishment of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) ' gray list', made up of countries that did not implement all international standards of tax cooperation.
At the commercial level, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Free Trade Treaty (CTA) which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The bigotute fountainer passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought, tireless, over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the claws of the evil Bowser, but he has never done so far in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month at shops around the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the characteristics of Nintendo 3DS laptop console, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the need to use glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy without glasses should work," said Nintendo's specialist press officer in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the video game presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game of Nintendo originally designed for that support", since so far successes such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo spokesperson has maintained that despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is a "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook up the less skilled users.
Once it has been exceeded, the most experienced will be able to take a "second turn" at the playing levels, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This Super Mario incursion into the three dimensions also involves the return of the character to a portable console, which did not take place since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo makes a guide to the followers of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of previous deliveries, consisting of that the moustache fountain will have to travel dangerous mined platforms in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find news in movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
