Weather conditions:
The ICM reports placed adequate conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft moves towards the boundary area between the DF and the State of Mexico with low-level cloud layers.
Selected paths:
It is likely that because of the cloud conditions the crew has sought a lower elevation area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar aircraft record coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersal of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far allows to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and side path.
The aircraft's debris pattern suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the sinister, there is still no evidence on the ship's remains of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest findings of the investigation indicate that he could have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9 thousand 200 feet above the average sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was allegedly disarticulated along that route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter could have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After thorough search in a wider area than the agreed site, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, which reinforces the presumption that the impact was presented in structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Security is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit of the Hospital de Specialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population to participate whether or not it is eligible, to attend IMSS sports units in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday starting at 8:00 hours.
He stressed that the protocol began at the Quauhtémoc Sports Unit (Posient Mexico State) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Mexico East State).
Once the objective of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is achieved, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the 14 November World Diabetes Day, the goal was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of their parents for the implementation of specific dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and inherited history of disease, with the aim of avoiding risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He explained that Saturdays apply to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (the genes associated with childhood obesity are identified).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that, in just six years, there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,' the IMSS expert pointed out.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics results in the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, allowing them to detect any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (canthosis) in neck and forearms, which indicate the probability of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential way, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (matals, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt of UNAM would prevent beaks
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 boats each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphalt floor is the right one, the boats could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his conference A technological opinion of the Basques, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of boats.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight ones, called asphaltenes, and other low molecular weights, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
Asphalt viscoelastic behavior is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes broken down, he added.
The above means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphaltic folder, made up of small rocks bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitute the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
In transiting vehicles and generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If they were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphaltic folder, there was plenty, a last layer called bearing folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e., a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, you should have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
As the part of the floor that is going to receive and disseminate the efforts, the treadmill also requires the appropriate thickness and the material that is made must be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is wet, the water spreads into the inside of the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a blanching of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of cows.
