Of the seven lophoscopists working in the ITC section, this week he was given the "availability" shift to Eliasar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
As he began his career, González worked in Chocó municipalities, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in loposcopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliasar warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
On Friday night he left for the Caucasus in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he should identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be of the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to take Guillermo León Sáenz's deductible card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was found, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter, and a flashlight, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man who came from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming to the Defense Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the fingerprint
For a fingerprint reader of the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliasar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without any margin of error, which can become key in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of captured persons.
When captured, many criminals have false papers or do not have papers.
We take the fingerprints and search them in the database.
The investigator told him that in a case of theft, he was touched by a piece of wall of a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint from all hands and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Marks may also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a mark on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that it was the killer, it does lie at the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that in the objects "prints are extracted with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or the Registration.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," the ITC expert said.
