Energy policy:
the facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate for an electoral meeting to be the time to reflect on such issues and on the location of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will double the electricity demand by 2050, unless a large part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, there will be an increasing shortage of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Germany therefore remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is not the case either of Belgium, which submits itss to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or Switzerland, which aims only to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, as a few examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, returning to the construction of a disrupted power plant after the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a speech.
The Berlin election will entail an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, harmful effects will be noted.
The case of Denmark must be considered.
Europe's wind champion, with 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest coal and gas users due to wind intermittent; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the record of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than those of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would remain realism to the wonderful declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
It is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not show any opposition to that kind of energy in principle, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Extensively export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and which can create non-replaceable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would involve the sacrifice of much of these SMEs and the loss of the €6 billion per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would charge an EPR designed to operate sixty years, when the downfall of its manufacturer is planned?
In order to solve the nuclear energy equation, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low-carbon and renewable CO2 solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a security authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing power stations and the construction of Flamenville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the reactor's design and to unforgivable human faults.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which caused the death of tens of thousands.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
As all electric actors who want to build a power plant study, the interruption of their construction in Flamenville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
