More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waitresses."
However, it is rarely considered from an economic point of view.
The question is, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the right-wing case, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers," while on the left, the tone fixed Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountainists.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande merely includes trivialities, indicating that the codesarroll will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge of immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limitation of immigration undermines growth and harms employment.
The fears associated with the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly those with low qualifications, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that immigrants are actually more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are primarily engaged in occupations in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national and most skilled workers in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on wages and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows represents a rise in real long-term wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of American Nobel prizes naturalized and business like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they provide an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization, for example, estimates that an immigrant who reaches 30 years of age in Germany will make a net contribution (early income) of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term of office, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go to look for the points of growth he lacked "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which deterred immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
