From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is rising
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, over which it had been suspected for a long time, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs Abdelkader Messahel even stated that Algiers already "has the certainty".
"The way in which both organizations operate and reports from intelligence services demonstrate that they are cooperating," he explained, providing no further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the gateways.
Kidnapped in a Niamey restaurant by persons related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian researchers discovered several telephone chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two figures particularly captured the interest of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, Boko Haram's cradle, and the other one to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly expect to have more formal evidence before speaking of operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys financial and intellectual support from abroad and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" have been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting in Washington, has since been pressing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, take time to consider the group as a community of illuminators unworthy of interest.
A quick hit
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It is polite and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants are launching the fight against the wicked central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and the attacks on the police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and registered 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that caused 80 deaths in Jos and then another one in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the police-protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of these.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international objective.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would range from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, worries all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and that the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
