The North Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Seabed, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the Baltic shores, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Netherlands counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned the steering wheel of the valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, each year, 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas will reach Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km communicating the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents a victory air.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding land travel by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it by closing its access to Western European markets.
At the high point of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact" in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater supply security.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and West Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the directors of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against anchorages of ships.
It is based at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields that date from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream society.
In addition, extreme measures were needed to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform in the waters of Sweden was planned, but the project officials gave up on the project, seeing that the Swedish people were not ready to allow a Russian state society to be permanently established in the sea in front of their coasts.
"In case it fails, we'll interrupt the gas pass in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released to the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that an escape will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, they will have a flight every 100,000 years.
Controlling the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, which conducts external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates through the inside of the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one metre, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
She joined the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
Its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
After that, Gazprom rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been brought to an end by 30 per cent with the contribution of the shareholders and 70 per cent by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of spending alone.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, with 4.5 meters of height, form the exit door of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
To total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a trademark.
Founded half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine chart is easily recognized, with its rectangular black pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskin books with the present appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a list of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, by that then company consultant, took charge of the launch of the new product.
The book is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (top hair), which refers to a tanned cotton that was used, inter alia, to cover banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, as the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and worshiped.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks into bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the height of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer wallpapers... The brand covers a wide range of media.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the whole population.
Disappointed?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made for fifteen years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"But there's still a lot left to do."
It should be mentioned that the unemployed persons with disabilities continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are older than 50 (a 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and "constitute the quid of the problem", says Christian Grapin, General Director of Tremplin, a partnership created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Engrepreneur Association for Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge on low disabilities", with "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of 1987.
According to the latest available figures, they date from 2008, they reach a 2.6% ratio.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for raising the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the establishment number "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law that increased contributions has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, in particular among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have employees with disabilities in their staff, compared to 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
